truth:
truth (keep, verified accurate): "Stop relying solely on programmatic permission checks like checkCallingOrSelfPermission; enforce the same custom permissions in the AndroidManifest.xml file. If you also add a programmatic check as defense-in-depth, it must fail closed (return/throw on denial) — logging and falling through is worse than no check at all."

code_bad (unchanged, still a fair negative example — fails open on log-only... but actually keep as illustrating "programmatic-only, no manifest backing"):
  int canProcess = checkCallingOrSelfPermission("com.example.perm.READ_INCOMING_MSG");
  if (canProcess != PERMISSION_GRANTED) throw new SecurityException();
  // still not recommended as the SOLE control -- no manifest enforcement shown

code_good (replace — show the actual OWASP-recommended fix, manifest enforcement, from the same MASTG page's "Custom Permissions" implementation example):
  <!-- AndroidManifest.xml -->
  <permission android:name="com.example.myapp.permission.START_MAIN_ACTIVITY"
      android:label="Start Activity in myapp"
      android:protectionLevel="signature" />
  <activity android:name=".SecureActivity"
      android:permission="com.example.myapp.permission.START_MAIN_ACTIVITY" />

  // optional defense-in-depth check -- must fail CLOSED, not just log:
  if (ContextCompat.checkSelfPermission(this, "com.example.myapp.permission.START_MAIN_ACTIVITY")
          != PackageManager.PERMISSION_GRANTED) {
      throw new SecurityException("Permission denied");
  }

source note to attach: the ContextCompat.checkSelfPermission Log.v-only snippet in MASTG-TEST-0024 is OWASP's audit cue ("whenever you see code like this, verify manifest enforcement exists"), not a secure reference implementation — do not extract it as code_good verbatim again.

Truth: "Bound-check (or use checked_mul / Layout::array, which check for overflow) the size computed from user input before allocating — multiplying an unchecked parsed size by an element size can wrap around in release builds and allocate less memory than intended." code_good should be corrected to the real CodeQL GOOD example: `const BUFFER_LIMIT: usize = 10 * 1024;

fn allocate_buffer(user_input: String) -> Result<*mut u8, Error> {
    let size = user_input.parse::<usize>()?;
    if size > BUFFER_LIMIT {
        return Err("Size exceeds limit".into());
    }
    let num_bytes = size * std::mem::size_of::<u64>();

    let layout = std::alloc::Layout::from_size_align(num_bytes, 1).unwrap();
    unsafe {
        let buffer = std::alloc::alloc(layout); // GOOD

        Ok(buffer)
    }
}` — alternatively, reviewer's checked_mul-based rewrite (`user_input.parse::<usize>()?.checked_mul(std::mem::size_of::<u64>()).ok_or(...)?`) or `Layout::array::<u64>(size)` are both acceptable equivalent fixes if the truth text is kept as-is, but the shipped code_good must be replaced either way since it currently duplicates code_bad's vulnerability. Fact occurs twice, identically, in both v2/extractor/experts/appsec/facts/FINAL.jsonl (line 362) and v2/extractor/experts/appsec/facts/codeql.jsonl (line 458) — both need the fix.

Rewrite truth to: "Only applies to Go modules whose go.mod `go` directive is <=1.21 (gosec G601 itself is scoped this way): don't take the address of a nested field of the range variable 'sample' when iterating over a value-type slice, because pre-1.22 the loop variable is a single reused copy, so any captured address ends up pointing at whatever the last iteration wrote. Fix (pre-1.22 code) by shadowing the loop variable inside the body before taking its address: `sample := sample` then `&sample.sub.name`. On Go 1.22+ (go.mod `go 1.22` or later), each iteration gets its own copy of the range variable automatically, this aliasing bug cannot occur, and gosec no longer raises G601 for such modules — do not flag this pattern in Go>=1.22 codebases." Also fix code_good so it actually differs from code_bad, e.g.: code_bad = `for _, sample := range samples {
	fmt.Println(&sample.sub.name)
}` ; code_good = `for _, sample := range samples {
	sample := sample
	fmt.Println(&sample.sub.name)
}` (with a comment noting this fix is unnecessary/moot on Go>=1.22).

truth (unchanged, still correct): "Do not perform arithmetic on a value before converting to a smaller type, as the intermediate result may overflow silently."

code_good must be replaced (current example is broken — it still overflows). Fixed version:
func addProp(x uint8) uint16 {
	// convert to the wider type FIRST, then add — the addition then happens
	// in uint16, so it cannot wrap. (uint16(x + 10) would be wrong: Go
	// converts the untyped constant 10 to uint8 to match x, so x+10 is
	// computed in uint8 and can wrap before the outer conversion ever runs.)
	return uint16(x) + 10
}
Also fix/remove the now-false comment "y = x + 10 is 10..265" from the old example (actual wrapped range was 0..255).

Keep `truth` unchanged (it is accurate: "Escape user input with regex::escape before interpolating into a regular expression pattern"). Fix only `code_good`'s two casing typos: `option<&'h str>` → `Option<&'h str>`, and `regex::new(&pattern)` → `Regex::new(&pattern)`. Full corrected code_good:
use regex::{escape, Regex};

fn get_value<'h>(key: &str, property: &'h str) -> Option<&'h str> {
    // GOOD: User input is escaped before being used in the regular expression.
    let escaped_key = escape(key);
    let pattern = format!(r"^property:{escaped_key}=(.*)$");
    let re = Regex::new(&pattern).unwrap();
    re.captures(property)?.get(1).map(|m| m.as_str())
}

